					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Fri Aug 23, 2013 2:14 am<br /><b>Posts:</b> 274
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I theorized that that was the reason why so many NES games have dual harmonies; it was just a coincidence it also happened to sound good.  If both squares were playing the same tune, if one of them were to be cut out for any reason, there would be a negligible loss in musical quality, as the song is still the same.  Likewise, it's very rare to find an NES game where each of the square waves have their own melody.  Astyanax is one such game, and as such, most sound effects are handled through the noise channel.  Astyanax also has some light sounding noise percussion, so you can't really tell whether it's gone or not.  Some games, like Silver Surfer, have crazy music, but when you play the game, the sound effects will greatly cripple the music, leading me to believe that the music and sound were developed at different times.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

